Package com.google.mu.util.stream

Class Case<T,​R>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.google.mu.util.stream.Case<T,​R>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.stream.Collector<T,​java.util.List<T>,​R>
    public abstract class Case<T,​R>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.stream.Collector<T,​java.util.List<T>,​R>
    Utility class to perform n-ary functional pattern matching on a list or a stream of input elements.

    A Case object can be used as a stand-alone Collector for a stream. For example: 

    
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.MoreCollectors.exactly;

 stream.collect(exactly((a, b, c) -> ...));
    Or as one of several possible cases passed to the static cases() method. For example: 
    
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.MoreCollectors.*;
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.Case.cases;

 Path path = pathComponents.stream()
     .filter(...)
     .collect(
         cases(
             exactly((parent, child) -> ...),
             exactly(fileName -> ...)));
    In the above example, if you have a List that may or may not match these cases, you can use the static match() method instead. It returns an Optional object so that you can handle the "no match" case. 
    
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.MoreCollectors.*;

 Optional<Path> path = Case.match(
     pathComponents,
     exactly((parent, child) -> ...),
     exactly(fileName -> ...),
     atLeast(root -> ...));
    Since:
    5.3

      • cases

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T,​R> java.util.stream.Collector<T,​?,​R> cases​(Case<? super T,​? extends R>... cases)
        Returns a Collector that will expand the input elements and transform them using the first from cases that matches. If no case matches the input elements, IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

        For example if a string could be in the form of <resource_name> with no qualifier, or in the form of <project>.<resource_name> with project as the qualifier, or in the form of <project>.<location>.<resource_name>, with both project and location qualifiers, you can handle all 3 cases using: 

        
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.MoreCollectors.exactly;
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.Case.cases;

 Substring.first('.').repeatedly().split(string)
     .collect(
         cases(
             exactly(resourceName -> ...),
             exactly((project, resourceName) -> ...),
             exactly(((project, location, resourceName) -> ...))));

      • match

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T,​R> java.util.Optional<R> match​(java.util.List<T> list,
                                                      Case<? super T,​? extends R>... cases)
        Expands the input elements in list and transforms them using the first from cases that matches. If no case matches the input elements, Optional.empty() is returned.

        For example, to switch among multiple possible cases: 

        
 import static com.google.mu.util.stream.MoreCollectors.*;

 Optional<R> result =
     Case.match(
         list,
         exactly((a, b) -> ...),
         atLeast((a, b, c) -> ...),
         empty(() -> ...));
